ns my primary concern, and if anything, the fact that the Chinese governmen=
t is clearly calling the shots ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/20=
25-01-14/china-discusses-sale-of-tiktok-us-to-musk-as-one-possible-option )=
 in terms of ByteDance=E2=80=99s response to this ban confirms my contentio=
n that TikTok was ultimately under control of the Chinese Communist Party.

What is clear is that it would have been far better to have acted in 2020, =
but at that point we were still in the =E2=80=9CPresident Trump supports th=
is so it must be bad=E2=80=9D era of politics. The great irony, of course, =
is that President-elect Trump is now opposed to the ban, for some combinati=
on of not wanting to give Meta more power ( https://truthsocial.com/@realDo=
naldTrump/posts/112058087970558736 ) , satisfying prominent supporters ( ht=
tps://www.politico.com/news/2024/03/01/trump-club-for-growth-00144547 ) , a=
nd the fact that Trump has found great success on TikTok ( https://www.scmp=
.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3291923/trump-favours-keeping-=
tiktok-us-after-billions-views-during-election-campaign ). Even so, it=E2=
=80=99s not clear that Trump can do anything about the January 19th deadlin=
e, which is one day before his inauguration (and it=E2=80=99s not as if he =
can directly undo an act of Congress).

The other less discussed reason for a ban is the fact that basically every =
U.S. consumer tech product is banned in China; I am sympathetic to the argu=
ment that the U.S. is supposed to be a free market, but at some point =E2=
=80=94 and Trump=E2=80=99s rhetoric on trade would seem to agree =E2=80=94 =
openness depends on a level playing field, which is certainly not the case =
when it comes to a product like TikTok.

And, speaking of freedom, while I think TikTok=E2=80=99s argument that the =
ban is a violation of the First Amendment doesn=E2=80=99t hold up =E2=80=94=
 there are other forums available to creators, and there is Supreme Court p=
recedent in terms of deference on such matters to national security concern=
s =E2=80=94 it is worth acknowledging that banning TikTok would destroy an =
immensely valuable asset for anyone with a following on the platform (indee=
d, this is an under-explored angle of the social media censorship debate: b=
anning users didn=E2=80=99t cost them money, but a following is a valuable =
asset nevertheless). That too is another reason why it would have been much=
 wiser to deal with this issue in 2020 than in 2025; the value destruction =
for TikTok users would have been much smaller.

Generational Implications
-------------------------

Now again, all of this analysis may be moot if the Supreme Court rules in B=
yteDance=E2=80=99s favor; it=E2=80=99s also possible that TikTok is sold at=
 the last minute to an American company. I noted previously ( https://strat=
echery.com/2024/does-vr-matter-modular-products-and-defining-new-markets-ti=
ktok-acquirers/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5=
