at the two most compelling acquirers from a business perspective are Amazon=
 or Walmart, thanks to the potential tie-in to their e-commerce businesses,=
 but there was a rumor earlier this week ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/a=
rticles/2025-01-14/china-discusses-sale-of-tiktok-us-to-musk-as-one-possibl=
e-option ) that Elon Musk/X could be the buyer; he=E2=80=99s obviously pala=
table to Trump, but also could be to China as well, given Tesla=E2=80=99s l=
arge presence in the country (which, needless to say, presents plenty of it=
s own complications).

TikTok did deny the rumor ( https://variety.com/2025/digital/news/tiktok-el=
on-musk-sale-china-pure-fiction-1236273557/ ) , but (1) it=E2=80=99s unlike=
ly that TikTok is in control of the process given that (2) it=E2=80=99s unl=
ikely that ByteDance is in control of the process since (3) the Chinese gov=
ernment is the entity that has the final say. Even in that light, though, i=
t makes total sense for ByteDance and China to carry this process to the ve=
ry last hour in the hope of a reprieve; indeed, the fact that the service i=
s planning on locking out existing users =E2=80=94 which isn=E2=80=99t requ=
ired by the law =E2=80=94 suggests that the goal is to raise an outcry and =
a last-minute change of heart.

All that noted, the most interesting and uncertain outcome is if the ban ac=
tually proceeds as planned, and TikTok just suddenly disappears. Trump is r=
ight that the most obvious potential beneficiary is Meta and Instagram with=
 its Reels product, but I think he =E2=80=94 and observers broadly =E2=80=
=94 are underestimating what a massive deal it would be for Meta to actuall=
y fill the TikTok void permanently.

As a way of explaining why, I had an interesting conversation with someone =
who operates in the consumer market, and he was casually referring to diffe=
rent generations by their dominant social network. There=E2=80=99s the Face=
book generation, the Instagram generation, and the youngest cohort is the T=
ikTok generation; for Instagram to extend its reach downwards by an additio=
nal generation would be a huge deal that would reverberate for years.

That=E2=80=99s also a reason why it might not happen: younger generations d=
on=E2=80=99t want to be on boomer social networks (and, I am sorry to annou=
nce, =E2=80=9Cboomer=E2=80=9D as an adjective for anything that is older th=
an you is here to stay, which is to say we are never getting rid of boomers=
). One potential beneficiary could actually be SnapChat, but there might al=
so be an opportunity for a new social network, rare and improbable though t=
hat may seem.

Xiaohongshu
-----------

For now the latest fad is Xiaohongshu =E2=80=94 Little Red Book =E2=80=94 a=
 Chinese video network that competes with Douyin, ByteDance=E2=80=99s versi=
on of TikTok within China. From a column on China Global Television Network=
=E2=80=99s website ( https://news.cgtn.com/news/2025-01-14/-TikTok-refugees=
-Great-divide-between-the-public-and-the-government-1A9HZ9gaUta/p.html ) (C=
GTN is the international arm of China Central Television, and is state-owne=
d):

The recent surge of foreign users flocking to a Chinese social media app Xi=
aohongshu, following the looming threat of TikTok=E2=80=99s ban in the U.S.=
, has given rise to the term =E2=80=9CTikTok refugees.=E2=80=9D This mass m=
igration to an alternative platform underscores a deeper divide between gov=
ernment policies and public sentiment. As Xiaohongshu climbed to the top of=
 Apple=E2=80=99s App Store on Monday, it became evident that many members o=
f the public remain unconvinced by the government=E2=80=99s rationale for t=
argeting TikTok.

At the heart of this issue lies the question of national security. The U.S.=
 government has repeatedly asserted that TikTok, owned by the Chinese compa=
ny ByteDance, poses a significant threat to U.S. national security due to p=
otential data privacy concerns and the possibility of foreign interference.

However, the public=E2=80=99s apparent disregard for these concerns, reflec=
ted in their enthusiastic adoption of Xiaohongshu, suggests a growing skept=
icism toward such claims. Some individuals have expressed a preference for =
using Chinese apps over American social platforms like Facebook, owned by U=
.S. tech giant Meta. Certain American bloggers have called on their followe=
rs to join them in downloading and using Xiaohongshu as a way to voice diss=
atisfaction with the U.S. government and Meta. Some of these bloggers have =
even planned a week-long boycott of Meta=E2=80=99s social media platforms i=
n protest. Abby (@abby4thepeople), a user on X, formerly Twitter, said thou=
sands of people downloading Xiaohongshu to spite the U.S. government, findi=
ng themselves having interactions with millions of Chinese citizens on the =
app and inadvertently undoing decades of U.S. propaganda.

There are already lots of humorous interactions happening on Xiaohongshu, b=
ut I chose this specific article both because it includes some interesting =
and pertinent facts about the situation, and is also a great explanation of=
 how China is going to take the wrong lessons from this episode. Specifical=
ly, the article frames the =E2=80=9CTikTok refugee=E2=80=9D phenomenon as p=
ublic dissatisfaction with the government, which of course it is, but what =
is lacking is the contextual understanding to realize that U.S. citizens ar=
e publicly dissatisfied with the government as a matter of birthright.

Indeed, you could make the case that from a certain perspective it is the T=
ikTok refugees that are the real U.S. propoganda: they are giving a middle =
finger to the U.S. government by freely expressing themselves on Xiaohongsh=
u, which is honestly kind of great, and also will be very hard for the Chin=
ese to grok. It=E2=80=99s not a good sign in terms of understanding that th=
e author of this column is relying on random Twitter user quotes to make th=
eir point, when the entire point is that Americans can and will say whateve=
r they want.

The problem for Xiaohongshu =E2=80=94 and the reason why I think this migra=
tion will be short-lived =E2=80=94 is that this contingent isn=E2=80=99t go=
ing to really give a damn about Xiaohongshu=E2=80=99s moderation/censorship=
 concerns. The reality is that one of the most important parts of censorshi=
p operating at scale is triggering self-censorship (keep in mind the note a=
bove about the loss entailed in a ban), and that=E2=80=99s just not going t=
o happen with TikTok refugees; what is much more likely is that Xiaohongshu=
 pulls itself from U.S. app stores in a week or two.

In the meantime, I=E2=80=99ll enjoy the memes, and who knows, maybe there w=
ill be some sort of value that comes from this sort of cultural exchange; i=
f anything, this little episode is a reminder of what was lost to the Great=
 Firewall, and to take this full circle, that itself is a reminder that Chi=
na started it.

